[1] Cayman Islands
Date: Mon 22 Oct 2007
Source: Cayman Netnews [edited]
<http://caymannetnews.com/news-2828--1-1--.html>


A total of 2 cases of dengue fever have been reported on Grand
Cayman, leading to fears of an outbreak in the Cayman Islands.

Commenting on the situation, Leader of Opposition Hon. McKeeva Bush
said, "I am concerned and dismayed that there are 2 confirmed cases
of dengue fever present on Grand Cayman and that there has been no
announcement from the Government to alert the public of the situation."

According to Mr. Bush, Government made a statement several weeks ago
asking people to be careful when they visit countries that have the
presence of dengue fever. At the same time, the Government suggested
that there were no active cases in the Cayman Islands, Mr. Bush alleged.

"This is most ingenuous of the Government since there are 2 confirmed
cases, one in George Town and one in West Bay," he said.

The Mosquito Research Control Unit (MRCU) is responsible for aerial
spraying of chemicals that kill adult and larval mosquitoes. However,
it is understood that one of its pilots has resigned, reducing the
emphasis that can be put on aerial prevention of the disease.

"They say that it is imported and isolated, as these 2 individuals
had travelled to 2 different countries before coming here," he said.

The Cayman Islands receives large numbers of immigrants and tourists,
many of whom tour the region before arriving here.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is not clear if these 2 cases are imported, which seems likely,
and not dengue virus infections acquired locally. If imported, they
are indeed isolated, and may not be a source of further virus
transmission. The article makes no mention about the status of _Aedes
ageypti_ mosquitoes on the islands.

A zoomable health map showing the location of the Cayman Islands can
be accessed at:
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=19.3,-81.2,6>. - Mod.TY]

******
[2] Jamaica
Date: Sat 20 Oct 2007
Source: Jamaica Gleaner [edited]
<http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20071020/lead/lead6.html>


The Ministry of Health and Environment yesterday reported that there
were 282 confirmed cases of dengue fever and 1770 suspected cases,
noting that this was a significant increase over the past week [week
of 14 Oct 2007].

The ministry also noted that there were 11 suspected cases of the
deadly dengue haemorrhagic fever.

Meanwhile, Dr. Sheila Campbell-Forrester, chief medical officer of
health said she was concerned that householders are not taking
prevention methods seriously.

"The most effective way to stop dengue is through the action of
householders ridding their surroundings of mosquito breeding sites,"
said Dr. Campbell-Forrester.

She noted that unless people clean up around the home and yard, there
will be a difficulty in reducing the cases of dengue fever.

Dr. Campbell-Forrester said persistent rains have also interrupted
control measures and produced more breeding sites for mosquitoes.

[Byline: Petrina Francis]

--
