******
[3] Barbados
Date: Thu 18 Oct 2007
Source: Nation News.com [edited]
<http://www.nationnews.com/story/303483509607883.php>


There were 255 cases of dengue fever recorded in Barbados up to the
end of September [2007] but no related deaths, says Chief Medical
Officer Dr. Joy St. John.

And she is urging continued vigilance, as there are 592 suspected
cases of the viral illness. However, she also said there were no
reported cases of the potentially deadly dengue haemorrhagic fever.

Speaking to the media yesterday morning [17 Oct 2007] after the
official opening ceremony of the National Blood Bank at Jemmotts
Lane, St. Michael, St. John urged householders and businesses to
ensure their surroundings were free from "mosquito breeding sources."

The health professional explained that the Ministry of Health and
private sector partners were doing their utmost to decrease the
mosquito population.

St. John said the updates on clinical management had been circulated
to doctors and the medics were cooperating with the Ministry of
Health by following the guidelines and informing of suspected cases.

She also said that while people did not like the fogging, it was
"very effective" in stopping "the transmission of the dengue virus
from an infected person to someone who does not have it."

[Byline: Donna Sealy]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Fogging provides short-term reduction of transmission by killing
adult mosquitoes. Long-term vector reduction requires elimination of
larval breeding sites, so that new adult mosquitoes are not produced.

A zoomable health map showing the location of Barbados can be accessed at:
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=13.2,-59.6,5>. - Mod.TY]

******
[4] Mexico
Date: Sun 21 Oct 2007
Source: China View [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-10/21/content_6917220.htm>


Dengue fever has left 6 people dead in Mexico so far this year, with
some 22 943 Mexicans infected with the disease, local media reported
on Saturday [20 Oct 2007].

Among the patients, some 5000 were infected with the fatal
hemorrhagic variant, Secretary of Health Jose Angel Cordoba
Villalobos was quoted as saying. With a booming tourism, the epidemic
has spread to more places in Mexico, he said.

In 2000, only one case of hemorrhagic variant was found in every 50
dengue cases, but this year [2007] the ratio has jumped to nearly one
in 5, he noted. In Mexico the existing 4 dengue virus [infections]
may develop into the hemorrhagic variant, but luckily the mortality
caused by the virus is still low, he added.

Dengue fever, a viral infection spread by the _Aedes aegypti_
mosquito, is a serious health problem in many Central American and
Caribbean countries. Its symptoms include high fever, nausea, rash,
backache and headache. Most mainstream dengue cases are not fatal,
but the hemorrhagic variant, which causes severe internal bleeding as
blood vessels collapse, kills one in 20 of the infected.

The World Health Organization said the only way to fight dengue is to
stamp out [vector] mosquitoes.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The high proportion of DHF cases suggests that there may be
significant under-reporting of non-DHF dengue virus infections. - Mod.TY]

******
[5 ] Honduras
Date: Wed 10 Oct 2007
Source: Terra [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://actualidad.terra.es/sociedad/articulo/aumentan_honduras_trece_muertos_dengue_1926115.htm>


The number of deaths in Honduras caused by DHF so far in 2007
increased to 13, the Secretary of Public Health announced
today [10 Oct 2007].

The official report did not provide specific details about the 13th
fatal DHF victim. At least 1230 cases of the DHF type [of dengue
infection] have been registered up to now. Health authorities have
registered 24 207 cases of classic dengue [fever].

The report added that the region of the Central District, which
includes Tegucigalpa, the Honduran capital, has had the greatest
incidence of fatal [dengue], followed by the departments [state or
province equivalents. - Mod.TY] of Cortez, in the north along the
Guatemalan border, El Paraiso y Olancho, both in the eastern part of
the country, along the Nicaraguan border.

In 2006, the number of DHF deaths was 6.

