[6] Brazil (Sao Paulo)
Date: Fri 19 Oct 2007
Source: Folha de Sao Paulo (in Portuguese trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/folha/cotidiano/ult95u337893.shtml>


Dengue epidemic hits 127 Sao Paulo [state] cities
---------------------------------------------
One in every 5 municipalities in Sao Paulo [state] is facing a dengue
epidemic a little more than 2 months after the beginning of summer, a
season when this disease usually become worse. There have been 16
deaths this year [2007] in the state. Of the 645 Sao Paulo cities,
127 have registered in this year [2007] at least 300 cases per 100
000 inhabitants, a level used by the Ministry of Health as the
criterion for characterization as an epidemic. The calculations were
based on the dengue disease registers of the Sao Paulo Center for
Epidemiologic Surveillance and population data of IBGE.

In the entire state, the situation has not been characterized as
epidemic. With 65 860 cases among 41 million inhabitants, the index
is 161 cases per 100 000 inhabitants.

During the start of the national campaign against dengue on Wednesday
[16 Oct 2007], the Minister of Health Jose Gomes Temporao affirmed
that the country "is living [through] a dengue epidemic," despite the
fact that the index [of cases per 100 000] is less than the criterion
[number] for it. In Brazil, there have been 481 316 people infected
[with dengue virus] in a population of 190 million inhabitants, or
253 [dengue] victims per 100 000 inhabitants.

He recalled that the number of cases of the disease increased 49.77
percent from January to September [2007], in relation to the same
period in 2006. In Sao Paulo the current number now is 24 percent
above that of all last year [2006] and 12 times more than in 2005,
when there were 5400 [dengue] cases.

Small cities are in a worse situation in Sao Paulo state. Sales is
the leader [in numbers of dengue cases] where 1 in 20 people had
dengue this year [2007].

The city of Sao Paulo, with 2339 [dengue] cases, is still considered
under control, but other medium-sized cities such as Sao Jose do Rio
Preto, Campinas, Ribeirao Preto and Bauru are facing epidemics.

During the cold season, when the mosquito vector has difficulty in
reproducing and the numbers of [dengue] cases normally diminish, the
numbers of cases registered by CVE did not stop. There were 400 in
July, 79 in August and 25 in September [2007].

None the less, Affonso Viviani Junior, director of SUCEN
(Superintendency of Endemic Control) of the Secretariat of Health of
the state, stated that the number of 127 cities with a [dengue]
epidemic index does not reflect the reality of the disease at this
moment. "This number appears [high] because the case index is
cumulative. Cases from the first epidemiological week are in this
[case] total. The behavior of the virus in recent weeks is outside of
any epidemic situation," he said.

According to Viviani, the circulation of the virus continues in a
maximum of 20 municipalities. "Up until mid-year [2007] we had
registered almost 65 000 cases. The other weeks since then until now
do not exceed 1000."

The Governor [of Sao Paulo state], Jose Serra, and the Secretary of
Health, Luiz Roberto Barradas Barata, yesterday [18 Oct 2007] said
that the state was having a [dengue] epidemic. Barradas repeated that
the percent increase of dengue in the state in relation to last year
[2006] is less than the peak of the national index.

Despite that the situation is not considered alarming, the costs to
the state for dengue in 2007 is R 40 million [22 309 000 USD. -
Mod.TY], double that of last year [2006]. The state also contracted
120 field agents for mosquito control.

--
