[8] Brazil (national)
Date: Wed 17 Oct 2007
Source: O Estado de Sao Paulo [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod. TY, edited]
<http://txt.estado.com.br:80/editorias/2007/10/17/ger-1.93.7.20071017.4.1.xml>


Dengue increases and the Minister admits that there is an epidemic in
the country
---------------------------------------------------
Brazil is experiencing a dengue epidemic. The number of [dengue]
cases reached 481 300 between January and September [2007],
practically 50 percent more than in the same period in 2006.

The Minister of Health, Jose Gomez Temporao, issued an alert
yesterday [16 Oct 2007], classifying the situation as "unjustifiable"
and "unacceptable" during the initiation of a national mobilization
campaign against the disease. Temporao also referred to the 121
deaths registered in the first 9 months of this year [2007], which is
less than the 150 deaths confirmed in 2002, the worst year for this
disease in the country.

According to Temporao, this high [death] index represents a
deficiency in [medical] attention for DHF [cases]. According to
Health Ministry data, there were 481 300 cases registered for the
country. During the same period last year [2006] there were 321 300 cases.

The Minister indicated that of this total this year [2007], 1067
persons contracted DHF, principally in the state of Mato Grosso do
Sul, Sao Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, Parana and Maranhao. In comparison
with the number of registered cases in 2006, the southern region had
the greatest increase in the [case] curve (828 [additional cases], 16
percent [increase]), followed by the east-central [region] (99, 95
percent increase), northern [region] (31 cases, 34 percent),
northeaster [region] (30 cases, 43 percent) and southeastern [region]
(19 cases, 81 percent).

In the recent [situation], the increase in [dengue] cases was boosted
by Rio (75 cases, 64 percent) and by Sao Paulo (20 cases, 75
percent), for a total of 64 310 [cases] notified up to September,
versus 53 259 [notified cases] in the same period last year [2006].
Minas and Espirito Santo presented negative results [compared to
2006], -5 [fewer cases], 22 percent [decline] and -27,92 percent, respectively.

"This is an epidemic. And this epidemic is worrisome," said Temporao,
citing the difficulty of combating _Aedes aegypti_, vector of the
disease [virus], and the variety of virus serotypes which "put
obstacles" in the way of vaccine development.

"Unhappily, this vaccine is not on the nearby horizon," indicated the Minister.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This situation now has become a ritual: every new health minister
(which have not been few), who shows fear, surprise and worry about
dengue, begins a group of new initiatives.

Dengue is controlled by a continuous effort, without interruptions,
not with bursts of actions that later cease or diminish ... and
requires years and years of work. - Mod.LJS]

[The WHO (World Health Organization) description of dengue fever and
the more deadly dengue hemorrhagic fever [DHF] can be found in
ProMED-mail's "Dengue/DHF update 20070514.1541." ProMED-mail thanks
the contributors to this update and encourages others to contribute
reports also. - Mod.TY]
